1 gavaA AlwaAdiI c
1. gavaA AlwaAdiI, (Msb, K,) aor. yagovuw, (Msb,) inf. n. gavowN; (Msb, K;) and gavaI, aor. yagoviI, inf. n. gavoyN; (K;) the latter mentioned by IJ, but the former is that which is [commonly] known to the lexicologists; (TA;) The valley, or water-course, was, or became, full of guvaMC [q. v.]: (Msb: [and the like is indicated in the K:]) or had in a abundance of camels' or similar dung (baEor) and leaves and reeds or canes. (TA.) ― -b2- gavaA AllRaHomu, inf. n. gavowN, The flesh-meat was bad by reason of its leanness. (IKtt, TA.) ― -b3- gavati AlnRafosu, (S, Msb, K,) aor. tagoviI, (S, Msb,) inf. n. gavoIN and gavayaAnN; (S, Msb, K;) and, accord. to Lth, gaviyat, aor. tagovaI, inf. n. gavFA, but Az says that this is post-classical; (TA;) i. q. xabuvat; (S, K, TA;) and jaAXat; (TA;) i. e. [The soul, or stomach, heaved; or became agitated by a tendency to vomit; or] became agitated so that the person nearly vomited, by reason of a mixture pouring forth to the mouth of the stomach: (Msb, TA:) or, as some say, gavayaAnN signifies a flowing of the mouth which sometimes, or often, occasions vomiting. (TA.) ― -b4- gavati AlsRamaMCu biAlsRaHaAbi, (K, TA,) aor. tagoviI, (TA,) The sky was, or became, clouded, or covered with clouds: (K, TA:) or began to be so. (TA.) ＝ -A2- gavaA AlsRayolu AlmarotaEa, aor. yagovuwhu, inf. n. gavowN; thus accord. to J, [in the S,] but accord. to the K and ISd, gavaI, mentioned in art. gvI; and in [some of] the copies of the K, AlmarobaEa is erroneously put for AlmarotaEa; (TA;) The torrent drew [or washed] together the pasture, and deprived it of its sweetness; as also AgvAhu↓. (S, K.) ― -b2- And hence, by way of comparison, (TA,) gavaI AlkalaAma, aor. yagoviyhi; (K, TA;) and gaviyahu, aor. yagovaAhu; (K, * TA;) the former verb of the class of ramaI, and the latter of the class of raDiIa; inf. n. gavoIN;
(TA;) (tropical:) He mixed, or put together confusedly, the speech, or language. (K, * TA.) ― -b3- And gavaI AlmaAla, and AlnRaAsa, He beat the cattle, and the people, and dealt blows among them. (K, * TA.) ― -b4- gaviyati AlOaroDu biAlnRabaAti The land became abundant in herbage: (K, TA:) or began to be so. (TA.) ― -b5- And gaviIa XaEoruhu, inf. n. gavFI, His hair became matted, or compacted together: mentioned in art. gvI by IKtt: perhaps a dial. var. of EaviIa, with the unpointed E; mentioned before. (TA.)

gumayoSaMCu c
gumayoSaMCu dim. of gamoSaMCu [fem. of OagomaSu]. (TA.) Hence, (TA,) AlgumayoSaMCu [The star Procyon;] one of the XiEorayaAni, (S, K,) whereof the other is AlXRiEoraI AlEabuwru [i. e. Sirius]: (TA:) the former is also called AlgamuwSu↓, (S, K,) and AlrRumayoSaMCu, (TA,) and AlXRiEoraI AlXRaAmiyRapu: (IAth:) it is one of the Mansions of the Moon [accord. to those who make the term nawoCN to signify the auroral setting;
namely, the Seventh]; (TA;) and is in the ciraAE; (S;) i. e., it is the greater of the two stars called AlcRiraAEu AlmaqobuwDapu: (IAth:) it is called AlgmySAC because of its smallness and its littleness of light [in comparison with the other XErI], from gamaSu AlEayoni: (TA:) [or the reason of its being so called is this:] the Arabs assert that the XiEorayaAni are the sisters of suhayol [or Canopus]; (IDrd, S;) and that they [three] were together; but that shyl descended into the south, and AlXRiEoraI AlyamaAniyRapu [which is Sirius] followed it; (IDrd;) this latter, they say, crossed the Milky way, and was therefore named AlEabuwru; and AlgmySAC remained in her place, weeping for the loss of the two others until her eye became affected with gamaS: (IDrd, K: *) they also assert that thou seest AlEbwr when she rises as though she desired to cross [the Milky Way] (kaOanRahaA tasotaEobiru); but AlgmySAC thou seest not [as yet in any part of Arabia], she having wept until she has become affected with gamaS. (S.)
